<headline>Special Weather Statement issued March 13 at 2:25PM EDT  by NWS Greenville-Spartanburg</headline>
<description>...PATCHY BLACK ICE POSSIBLE ACROSS MUCH OF THE MOUNTAINS OF
WESTERN NORTH CAROLINA MONDAY MORNING...
Considerable snow cover persisted late Sunday in the mountains of
western North Carolina, particularly near the Tennessee border.
With temperatures rising a little above the freezing mark in most
mountain locations Sunday afternoon, some melting has occurred.
Temperatures falling into the mid to upper 20s overnight will
allow this water and slush to refreeze, posing a threat of patchy
black ice on area roadways.
If driving in the western mountains on Monday morning, be on the
lookout for slippery spots on area roadways. Consider allowing
for extra travel time and reduced speeds. Temperatures should warm
above the freezing mark in most western mountain locations by
around 9 am EDT.</description>
